{
  "doc_id": "8132",
  "text": "Few studies have been conducted comparing HIV-POCT using finger stick whole blood in field conditions with a laboratory GS. Specificity in data from the current study was high; we found very low levels of false positive rapid test results, in contrast to some studies [CITATION_1] . Published data on sensitivity of HIV rapid tests in the field vary. One study from SA nested within the Good Start Trial showed sensitivity of 98% when comparing HIV-POCT tests with laboratory-based HIV tests [CITATION_2] , whereas another South African study measured accuracy of HIV-POCT testing in a clinic setting and found high rates of false negative HIV tests (sensitivity 69%, 95% CI: 41-89%) which was improved by introduction of a different testing algorithm and QA measures [CITATION_3] . The authors concluded that user error was the most significant contributor to inaccuracy.",
